==Translingual==

===Etymology===
{{L.}} exceptio: exception quod: based on metus: duress causa: a cause (of action).

===Phrase===
'''exceptio quod metus causa'''.

#{{Law}} Also known as the [[exceptio metus]]; an [[exception]] based on the fact that the underlying cause of action was based on [[duress]] or intimidation by the [[plaintiff]] of the defendant.
#*It appears that in that Court, the defence stressed by appellant's counsel was the '''exceptio quod metus causa''' and it was to that defence that the learned Judge-President mainly directed himself. ''SHEPSTONE v SHEPSTONE  1974 (2) SA 462 (N)''
#*Reverting to the defence raised by first defendant, it is clear that a contract may be [[vitiate]]d by duress ('''metus'''), the [[raison d'etre]] of the rule apparently being that [[intimidation]] or improper pressure renders the consent of the party subjected to duress no true consent at all. ''AREND AND ANOTHER v ASTRA FURNISHERS (PTY) LTD  1974 (1) SA 298 (C)''

====Common exceptions====
*For a list of common [[exceptions]] see [[exceptio]].